WEBVTT

00:00:15.682 --> 00:00:16.683
Here I go!

00:00:30.071 --> 00:00:33.450
I need to release the brake

00:00:35.660 --> 00:00:40.165
and that allows the stop to go through.

00:00:45.503 --> 00:00:47.797
So this whole unit, I believe,

00:00:47.797 --> 00:00:51.885
has been here since when they first built the building.

00:00:59.350 --> 00:01:01.853
There were two prior owners

00:01:01.853 --> 00:01:05.522
to this building going residential.

00:01:05.940 --> 00:01:08.068
It was originally a stable.

00:01:08.068 --> 00:01:10.695
All the carriages were on the ground floor

00:01:10.695 --> 00:01:13.238
and all the horses came up

00:01:13.239 --> 00:01:16.284
because real estate, even over 100 years ago,

00:01:16.284 --> 00:01:17.243
was so expensive.

00:01:17.243 --> 00:01:20.705
It was cheaper to go up, as opposed to go wider.

00:01:24.626 --> 00:01:28.421
Starting at the end of the Civil War up until 1900,

00:01:28.421 --> 00:01:31.508
this area was really the epicenter of New York City.

00:01:31.508 --> 00:01:34.344
All the wealthier citizens would have had carriages,

00:01:34.344 --> 00:01:36.012
and they would have needed to keep

00:01:36.012 --> 00:01:39.099
their horses and stables relatively near their homes.

00:01:39.099 --> 00:01:41.768
So there must have been quite
a few stables in the area.

00:01:41.768 --> 00:01:44.187
It was just something that was central to the culture.

00:01:45.105 --> 00:01:47.232
One of the major reasons this area

00:01:47.232 --> 00:01:50.568
started developing was the building of the Fifth Avenue Hotel

00:01:50.568 --> 00:01:53.029
at the corner of 23rd and Fifth Avenue.

00:01:53.905 --> 00:01:57.909
The building with the elevator
would have been located right about here,

00:01:57.909 --> 00:02:02.831
and then about a block and a half away
would have been the Fifth Avenue Hotel.

00:02:02.831 --> 00:02:06.459
It occupied the whole side of Broadway
and Fifth Avenue here.

00:02:07.085 --> 00:02:10.505
The building with the elevator was probably built in 1888

00:02:10.505 --> 00:02:13.841
and at that time it was a five-story brick stable,

00:02:13.842 --> 00:02:16.344
and the owner was E.A. Darling,

00:02:16.344 --> 00:02:19.513
who was connected with the Fifth Avenue Hotel.

00:02:19.514 --> 00:02:22.934
He was in charge of buying all the food for the hotel.

00:02:22.934 --> 00:02:26.603
So I think they were just entrepreneurs
and they saw an opportunity to invest

00:02:26.604 --> 00:02:28.022
and make some more money.

00:02:28.690 --> 00:02:30.567
The elevator was new at that time.

00:02:30.567 --> 00:02:33.403
Before the advent of the elevator,

00:02:33.403 --> 00:02:35.947
the higher rooms were considered to be less desirable

00:02:35.947 --> 00:02:38.533
because people had to walk up all those stairs.

00:02:38.533 --> 00:02:41.077
But with the introduction of elevators,

00:02:41.077 --> 00:02:43.913
they became the most desirable rooms.

00:02:53.756 --> 00:02:57.051
We’ve been actually grandfathered,

00:02:57.051 --> 00:02:59.012
but they passed the new safety law

00:02:59.012 --> 00:03:01.014
and I think in 2025,

00:03:01.014 --> 00:03:02.807
all of these will be outlawed.

00:03:02.807 --> 00:03:06.518
So we’re just getting a jump on it
and trying to replace it now.

00:03:07.020 --> 00:03:09.230
I’m sort of sorry to see it go.

00:03:09.230 --> 00:03:12.233
Although it would be nice to have a push-button elevator.

00:03:28.499 --> 00:03:29.167
Hello.

00:03:29.709 --> 00:03:30.960
Hey, good morning.

00:03:30.960 --> 00:03:32.420
Morning, how are you?

00:03:35.173 --> 00:03:37.342
This is Tony, I’m Mark.

00:03:37.342 --> 00:03:38.509
- Nice to meet you.
- I don’t want to shake your hand.

00:03:38.509 --> 00:03:39.636
I’m already all dirty.

00:03:39.636 --> 00:03:41.930
Okay, no problem.

00:03:44.641 --> 00:03:46.601
I feel really sad.

00:03:46.601 --> 00:03:47.852
Really sad.

00:03:47.852 --> 00:03:49.354
I love this elevator.

00:03:49.354 --> 00:03:53.024
Been using it for 40 years or more actually

00:03:53.024 --> 00:03:57.278
and I’m sorry to see it go.

00:03:57.278 --> 00:03:58.571
Well, would you like to do the honors?

00:03:59.113 --> 00:03:59.781
Oh, boy.

00:03:59.781 --> 00:04:00.615
Okay.

00:04:05.787 --> 00:04:07.121
She goes.

00:04:07.121 --> 00:04:08.289
There she goes.

00:04:09.874 --> 00:04:11.000
Still shaking.

00:04:11.876 --> 00:04:12.669
Yeah.

00:04:13.878 --> 00:04:15.755
So what are you guys doing this morning?

00:04:15.755 --> 00:04:19.216
This morning I’m going to be hanging this thing up above us.

00:04:19.216 --> 00:04:20.885
Cutting the cables off the elevator.

00:04:20.885 --> 00:04:22.135
Oh, no.

00:04:22.136 --> 00:04:23.471
So this will be the last ride.

00:04:23.471 --> 00:04:26.057
Should be the last time it runs on its own power.

00:04:26.057 --> 00:04:26.849
Wow.

00:04:26.849 --> 00:04:29.227
The electrical cables?

00:04:29.227 --> 00:04:29.727
All of them.

00:04:29.727 --> 00:04:30.686
Everything.

00:04:30.687 --> 00:04:33.106
The hoist cables, the electrical cables, everything.

00:04:33.106 --> 00:04:34.065
Everything comes down.

00:04:34.065 --> 00:04:35.191
Going to the basement?

00:04:35.191 --> 00:04:36.025
Yeah.

00:04:40.405 --> 00:04:41.239
Well...

00:04:42.365 --> 00:04:43.574
I think it’s sad.

00:04:43.574 --> 00:04:44.075
I know.

00:04:44.075 --> 00:04:45.034
It’s bittersweet.

00:04:45.034 --> 00:04:45.909
Yes.

00:04:51.541 --> 00:04:52.500
Hi.

00:04:55.128 --> 00:04:58.965
Change is very difficult, in its way.

00:04:58.965 --> 00:05:00.215
I’m used to change.

00:05:00.425 --> 00:05:02.802
I generally welcome it.

00:05:10.351 --> 00:05:12.312
Every time I get into the elevator,

00:05:12.312 --> 00:05:13.938
I think about the horses.

00:05:13.938 --> 00:05:15.315
I really do.

00:05:15.648 --> 00:05:19.360
And what it must have been like to be in that elevator

00:05:19.360 --> 00:05:21.487
with a 2,000-pound horse.

00:05:22.196 --> 00:05:23.406
Very sobering.

00:05:28.578 --> 00:05:31.289
This thing has been a part of my life for a while now.

00:05:31.289 --> 00:05:36.127
It’s surreal to think that this is the last time we’re going to do this.

00:05:36.627 --> 00:05:38.087
Out with the old, in with the new.

00:05:38.087 --> 00:05:38.755
Yeah.

00:05:38.755 --> 00:05:39.796
This one’s different though.

00:05:39.797 --> 00:05:41.758
We’ve taken on a lot of elevators before,

00:05:41.758 --> 00:05:43.760
but nothing really like this.

00:05:43.760 --> 00:05:46.179
Nothing that was designed to haul horses up and down.

00:05:46.179 --> 00:05:47.138
Yeah.

00:05:48.556 --> 00:05:49.515
And that’s it.

00:05:49.807 --> 00:05:52.101
Last time it comes up on its own power.

00:05:57.690 --> 00:05:59.901
So when Tony goes to go up at the elevator,

00:05:59.901 --> 00:06:00.860
that’s your knife switch.

00:06:00.860 --> 00:06:02.195
One side of that is up.

00:06:02.195 --> 00:06:03.111
One side of that is down.

00:06:03.112 --> 00:06:04.447
Tony, go up with the rope.

00:06:04.447 --> 00:06:05.073
Going up.

00:06:05.448 --> 00:06:07.032
It’s got to rotate,

00:06:07.033 --> 00:06:07.784
flop over,

00:06:07.784 --> 00:06:08.784
make contact.

00:06:08.785 --> 00:06:09.702
Up he goes.

00:06:10.703 --> 00:06:11.787
Turn the motor,

00:06:11.788 --> 00:06:13.873
which turns the gear up there,

00:06:13.873 --> 00:06:15.082
and the bottom there is a worm gear,

00:06:15.083 --> 00:06:15.958
it looks like a screw.

00:06:16.292 --> 00:06:17.501
And on top, if you look in the back,

00:06:17.502 --> 00:06:18.628
you’ll see the drum,

00:06:18.628 --> 00:06:19.628
which has the cables on it.

00:06:19.629 --> 00:06:21.672
That's moving the car up and the counterweight down

00:06:21.672 --> 00:06:22.757
at the same time.

00:06:24.967 --> 00:06:26.803
This is the only one I’ve ever seen like this

00:06:26.803 --> 00:06:27.594
in my whole career.

00:06:28.221 --> 00:06:30.181
As the rules change and the laws change,

00:06:30.181 --> 00:06:32.683
it’s harder to make those old ones meet the new codes.

00:06:32.683 --> 00:06:33.893
That’s what happened here.

00:06:33.893 --> 00:06:34.643
At this point,

00:06:34.644 --> 00:06:35.728
you can't meet new codes.

00:06:35.728 --> 00:06:37.939
You can’t do a brake test on an elevator like this.

00:06:37.939 --> 00:06:40.358
At some point, it’s just time.

00:06:41.025 --> 00:06:43.193
Come back down, Tony.

00:06:43.194 --> 00:06:46.197
So now he’s going to go the other way with it.

00:06:56.082 --> 00:06:56.998
This blue thing right here,

00:06:56.999 --> 00:06:58.501
this was added later on.

00:06:58.501 --> 00:07:01.671
That’s a more modern brake than—

00:07:05.299 --> 00:07:07.551
This thing just freaking exploded.

00:07:07.552 --> 00:07:08.553
The motor just blew up.

00:07:08.553 --> 00:07:09.512
Ghost.

00:07:10.054 --> 00:07:11.179
Amazing.

00:07:11.180 --> 00:07:12.598
What were the odds?

00:07:14.142 --> 00:07:16.853
How far are you away from the top, Tony?

00:07:16.853 --> 00:07:18.521
The motor just shorted.

00:07:20.523 --> 00:07:22.358
Did a little more than spark.

00:07:23.359 --> 00:07:24.277
It’s like a reality show.

00:07:24.277 --> 00:07:25.236
We didn’t even plan for this.

00:07:25.236 --> 00:07:26.070
No.

00:07:26.070 --> 00:07:27.488
Good thing you’re getting a new elevator.

00:07:28.281 --> 00:07:29.866
Because if you weren’t, now you would be.

00:07:29.866 --> 00:07:30.407
Yes.

00:07:30.950 --> 00:07:33.077
Can you climb out of the elevator at all?

00:07:36.456 --> 00:07:38.291
The motor shorted out, yeah.

00:07:38.291 --> 00:07:39.167
And he was coming down.

00:07:39.167 --> 00:07:41.919
It was in downward flight for about 30 seconds

00:07:41.919 --> 00:07:45.006
and then all of a sudden, it went bzzzzt

00:07:45.006 --> 00:07:46.715
and that was the end of it.

00:07:48.593 --> 00:07:51.512
That adds a lot of complication to this job.

00:07:51.512 --> 00:07:53.181
Like, a lot.

00:07:53.181 --> 00:07:53.722
Smoke?

00:07:53.723 --> 00:07:54.474
Oh, yeah.

00:07:55.975 --> 00:07:58.561
If you can, I think I need you to come here.

00:07:58.561 --> 00:08:01.354
Gerard’s coming and Chris is on his way.

00:08:01.355 --> 00:08:04.066
We’ll get this thing moving one way or another.

00:08:04.066 --> 00:08:05.234
Alright.

00:08:06.194 --> 00:08:07.737
So what do we have here?

00:08:08.654 --> 00:08:09.489
How you been?

00:08:09.489 --> 00:08:10.280
Good to see you.

00:08:10.281 --> 00:08:11.866
Yeah, good to see you.

00:08:12.450 --> 00:08:13.493
You sad?

00:08:13.493 --> 00:08:14.409
I am sad.

00:08:14.410 --> 00:08:15.536
She was.

00:08:15.536 --> 00:08:16.829
I am too, to be honest with you.

00:08:16.829 --> 00:08:18.664
I am really sad to see this go.

00:08:18.998 --> 00:08:20.750
She was just saying all these nice things about it.

00:08:20.750 --> 00:08:23.836
That’s like going down with the woman down the aisle

00:08:23.836 --> 00:08:26.172
and getting married and she dies of a heart attack, huh?

00:08:26.881 --> 00:08:27.672
Right.

00:08:29.592 --> 00:08:30.926
So it won’t move at all?

00:08:30.927 --> 00:08:32.428
No, can’t get it to go.

00:08:32.761 --> 00:08:34.429
I can’t get it to go up or down right now.

00:08:34.429 --> 00:08:35.180
Nothing.

00:08:37.642 --> 00:08:39.852
After 150 years, you break the freaking elevator?

00:08:39.852 --> 00:08:40.520
I know.

00:08:40.520 --> 00:08:42.938
It's not my fault, but now it's my problem.

00:08:42.938 --> 00:08:44.147
Where’s the hoist?

00:08:44.148 --> 00:08:45.316
In the elevator.

00:08:47.443 --> 00:08:48.319
Alright.

00:08:49.111 --> 00:08:50.112
Go to work.

00:08:50.112 --> 00:08:50.863
Yeah.

00:08:59.497 --> 00:09:01.665
So we came here yesterday to survey the job.

00:09:02.124 --> 00:09:04.710
There’s challenges with this one because of its age.

00:09:05.211 --> 00:09:08.089
So in this age bracket that I’ve been around,

00:09:08.089 --> 00:09:09.173
there’s definitely, I would say,

00:09:09.173 --> 00:09:12.051
less than a dozen left total in the city.

00:09:12.051 --> 00:09:13.719
I’ve put hands on three of them.

00:09:14.720 --> 00:09:16.764
I like that there's not many of them.

00:09:17.265 --> 00:09:20.643
Who really could say that they got to take an elevator out like this.

00:09:20.643 --> 00:09:22.562
Most people in our industry have never even seen

00:09:22.562 --> 00:09:23.980
an elevator with a leather belt before.

00:09:23.980 --> 00:09:26.691
I’ve showed people videos and pictures 
of this thing throughout time

00:09:26.691 --> 00:09:28.150
and they’ve never seen anything like it.

00:09:28.150 --> 00:09:30.778
So it’s cool to be a part of something like that

00:09:30.778 --> 00:09:32.572
and it's cool to possess the skills

00:09:32.572 --> 00:09:34.073
and know how to work on this.

00:09:34.073 --> 00:09:35.908
I take a lot of pride in the fact that

00:09:35.908 --> 00:09:37.910
our team knows how to do this.

00:09:44.250 --> 00:09:45.209
We deal with plumbing,

00:09:45.209 --> 00:09:46.544
we deal with electricity,

00:09:46.544 --> 00:09:49.630
we deal with every aspect of a building you could think of.

00:09:49.630 --> 00:09:51.465
We have to dabble in it somehow.

00:09:51.465 --> 00:09:53.009
You can’t Google this stuff.

00:09:53.009 --> 00:09:55.177
Anybody that put anything like this in

00:09:55.177 --> 00:09:57.263
has been dead before I was born.

00:09:57.263 --> 00:10:00.433
Part of our job is going to the job,

00:10:00.433 --> 00:10:01.976
engineering it in your mind

00:10:01.976 --> 00:10:04.020
so you could figure out how this thing comes apart

00:10:04.020 --> 00:10:05.021
and then doing it.

00:10:05.021 --> 00:10:06.896
But it's the first time you’ll ever do that.

00:10:06.897 --> 00:10:08.524
And probably the last time.

00:10:09.275 --> 00:10:11.736
But you have to be really good at it the one time you do it.

00:10:14.822 --> 00:10:17.241
Will you miss working on this elevator?

00:10:17.241 --> 00:10:19.201
No, I will not.

00:10:19.827 --> 00:10:21.746
I won’t miss working on this, no.

00:10:24.081 --> 00:10:24.915
So right now,

00:10:24.915 --> 00:10:26.791
the elevator is being held up by an electric chain hoist.

00:10:27.209 --> 00:10:29.002
We’re going to lower the car down to the basement.

00:10:29.003 --> 00:10:30.588
We’re going to clear out the cables

00:10:30.588 --> 00:10:32.423
that we just lowered down.

00:10:32.423 --> 00:10:33.132
And then from there,

00:10:33.132 --> 00:10:35.217
we will take off a wall of the cab

00:10:35.217 --> 00:10:36.761
to start removing the counterweights.

00:10:36.761 --> 00:10:37.844
From the top to the bottom,

00:10:37.845 --> 00:10:39.597
one by one, we’ll take them out of the rack

00:10:39.597 --> 00:10:41.473
and put them in the elevator with us

00:10:41.474 --> 00:10:42.892
until the counterweights are removed.

00:10:43.225 --> 00:10:45.436
The elevator’s last ride was when it came up.

00:10:45.436 --> 00:10:47.063
There’s no power going to the elevator right now.

00:10:47.063 --> 00:10:48.021
The main line is out,

00:10:48.022 --> 00:10:49.857
locked out so no one else can touch it.

00:10:49.857 --> 00:10:51.858
And that was just being manually run by a hoist.

00:10:51.859 --> 00:10:53.819
Only by elevator personnel.

00:11:08.751 --> 00:11:10.086
There’s a part of me, of course,

00:11:10.086 --> 00:11:11.379
that’s very happy.

00:11:14.256 --> 00:11:15.757
But I miss it.

00:11:16.509 --> 00:11:19.136
And I knew I was going to miss it.

00:11:21.430 --> 00:11:24.099
It’s very bittersweet.
